## Files
- scripts/migrations/migrate-measured-trees-to-dwc-occurrences.js (modify)

## Context
The ATProto blob spec states: 'After a successful upload, blobs are placed in temporary storage. Servers should garbage collect un-referenced temporary blobs after an appropriate time span.' A blob MUST be referenced by a record before the GC window expires or it gets deleted.

The current script uploads up to 3 photo blobs (trunk, leaf, bark) THEN creates the occurrence record. If the script crashes between blob uploads and record creation, the uploaded blobs are orphaned in temporary storage and will be garbage collected by the PDS.

## What to do
Restructure the main processing loop (lines 865-952) to use an **atomic blob referencing pattern**:

### Step 1: Create the occurrence record FIRST, without any photo blobs
```javascript
// Create the base occurrence record immediately (no evidence fields)
await agent.com.atproto.repo.putRecord({
  repo: did,
  collection: DWC_OCCURRENCE_COLLECTION,
  rkey: occurrenceRkey,
  record: occurrenceRecord  // no trunkEvidence/leafEvidence/barkEvidence yet
})
```

### Step 2: For EACH photo, upload blob then IMMEDIATELY update the record
```javascript
// Upload trunk photo
if (trunkUrl) {
  const result = await processPhoto(agent, trunkUrl, 'trunk', tmpDir)
  if (result && !result.skipped) {
    occurrenceRecord.trunkEvidence = result
    // IMMEDIATELY update the record to reference this blob
    await agent.com.atproto.repo.putRecord({
      repo: did,
      collection: DWC_OCCURRENCE_COLLECTION,
      rkey: occurrenceRkey,
      record: occurrenceRecord
    })
  }
}

// Upload leaf photo
if (leafUrl) {
  const result = await processPhoto(agent, leafUrl, 'leaf', tmpDir)
  if (result && !result.skipped) {
    occurrenceRecord.leafEvidence = result
    // IMMEDIATELY update the record to reference this blob
    await agent.com.atproto.repo.putRecord({
      repo: did,
      collection: DWC_OCCURRENCE_COLLECTION,
      rkey: occurrenceRkey,
      record: occurrenceRecord
    })
  }
}

// Same for bark...
```

This ensures every uploaded blob is referenced by the record within milliseconds of upload. If the script crashes after uploading trunk but before leaf, the trunk blob is safe (already referenced) and the script can resume and add leaf/bark later.

### Step 3: Handle the resume case for partially-migrated records
When the script encounters an existing occurrence record (idempotency check on line 863), it currently skips entirely. Instead, it should:
